6000|$|... [Footnote 21: Of {{course there}} remains the {{question}} whether, before the stage here recognized, there {{had already been}} produced a high temperature by those collisions of celestial masses which reduced the matter to a nebulous form. As suggested in First Principles (ยง 136 in the edition of 1862, and ยง 182 in subsequent editions), there must, after there have been effected all those minor dissolutions which follow evolutions, remain to be effected the dissolutions of the great bodies in and on which the minor evolutions and dissolutions have taken place; and it was argued that such dissolutions will be, at some time or other, effected by those immense transformations of molar motion into molecular motion, consequent on collisions: the argument being based on the statement of Sir John Herschel, that in clusters of stars collisions must inevitably occur. It may, however, be objected that though such a result may be reasonably looked for in closely aggregated assemblages of stars, {{it is difficult to}} conceive of its taking place throughout our Sidereal System at large, the members of which, and their intervals, may be roughly figured as pins-heads 50 miles apart. It would seem that something <b>like</b> <b>an</b> <b>eternity</b> must elapse before, by ethereal resistance or other cause, these can be brought into proximity great enough to make collisions probable.] ...|$|E
